(143, 'ANZA', '82997e11-2a1c-4b96-a5dc-163042c9efe7', 'Anza Ohyama;Ś§ßŚĪĪ„āĘ„É≥„ā∂', 'ŇĆmura[bf09723c-b799-403e-81ef-25b14d07b817]', '100073[2db42837-c832-3c27-b4a3-08198f75693c]', '1976-05-04', NULL, '152;151;150;149;148;147;146;145;144;153;142', '200012', '2000707', '1', '[Discogs (6)‚Ė†https://www.discogs.com/artist/7332992];[Spotify (3)‚Ė†https://open.spotify.com/artist/6FqPSlvSUeyjs1trbw649Q];[Deezer (3)‚Ė†https://www.deezer.com/artist/1455909];[IMDb (6)‚Ė†https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1024983/];[Official Website (2)‚Ė†http://www.anza.jp/];[Generasia (6)‚Ė†https://www.generasia.com/wiki/ANZA];[Apple Music (3)‚Ė†https://music.apple.com/jp/artist/1541170551];[Wikidata (6)‚Ė†https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3290395];[Rutracker (5)‚Ė†https://rutracker.org/forum/tracker.php?nm=ANZA];[The Pirate Bay (5)‚Ė†https://thepiratebay.org/search.php?q=ANZA&audio=on];[Wikipedia (6)‚Ė†https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANZA];[Genius (7)‚Ė†https://genius.com/artists/ANZA];[MusicBrainz (6)‚Ė†https://musicbrainz.org/artist/82997e11-2a1c-4b96-a5dc-163042c9efe7];[Instagram (2)‚Ė†https://www.instagram.com/anzahpp]', 'Anza Ohyama (Japanese: Ś§ßŚĪĪ „āĘ„É≥„ā∂, Hepburn: ŇĆyama Anza; born May 4, 1976), also known mononymously as ANZA, is a Japanese singer and actress. She is most widely recognized for her record-breaking tenure as the protagonist Usagi Tsukino in the Sailor Moon stage musicals (Sera Myu) and as the lead vocalist of the heavy metal band Head Phones President. Born in Cape Town, South Africa, to a Japanese father and a white South African mother, Ohyama moved to Nagasaki, Japan, during her childhood. Her multicultural background and initially limited Japanese fluency led to early challenges, including being bullied, which she has cited as a formative experience in her personal and artistic development. Ohyama‚Äôs career began in 1992 as a member of the idol group Sakurakko Club and its spin-off duo Momo. Her mainstream breakthrough came in 1993 when she was cast as the first-ever live-action Sailor Moon. \nBetween 1993 and 1998, Ohyama performed in 13 separate Sailor Moon musical productions, making her the longest-running actress to portray the character. Her rendition of the song \"La Soldier\" became a fan favorite, eventually being incorporated into the Sailor Moon R anime series. Beyond the franchise, she has established a successful career in musical theatre. Following her \"graduation\" from the Sailor Moon musicals, Ohyama transitioned from J-pop to a significantly heavier musical style. In 1999, she formed Head Phones President, a heavy metal band known for its blending of aggressive instrumentation with her versatile vocal range, which spans from melodic singing to intense screaming. The band has gained a cult following internationally, performing at major festivals in the United States, Europe, and South America. Ohyama also performed the opening theme \"Tobira o Akete\" for the Cardcaptor Sakura anime and has collaborated with various rock and metal projects, including the supergroup Vitamin-Q.', 'http://127.0.0.1:8887//Music/A/ANZA/Audio/Singles/1999.04.21. Tobira wo Akete/01. Tobira wo Akete.mp3^http://127.0.0.1:8887//Music/A/ANZA/Audio/Singles/1999.04.21. Tobira wo Akete/02. Mienai Chizu.mp3', 'śČČ„āí„Āā„ĀĎ„Ā¶‚Ė†Tobira wo Akete‚Ė†‚Äú„āČ„Āó„ĀŹ\"„ĀĄ„Āć„Āĺ„Āó„āá‚Ė†Rashiku Ikimasho‚Ė†Tobira wo Akate‚Ė†Mienai Chizu‚Ė†Right In The Night‚Ė†Tobira wo Akete (TV Size)‚Ė†Tobira o Akete‚Ė†Let Go‚Ė†Ť¶č„Āą„Ā™„ĀĄŚúįŚõ≥‚Ė†Kanata he‚Ė†ŚĹľśĖĻ„Āł‚Ė†‚Äú„āČ„Āó„ĀŹ\"„ĀĄ„Āć„Āĺ„Āó„āá(śė†ÁĒĽ„āĶ„ā§„āļ)‚Ė†Rashiku Ikimasho (Movie Size)‚Ė†‚Äú„āČ„Āó„ĀŹ\"„ĀĄ„Āć„Āĺ„Āó„āá (off vocal ver.)‚Ė†Thunder In My Heart‚Ė†Tsubasa‚Ė†Vidro Quebrado‚Ė†tobira o akete (Tobira o akete)‚Ė†śČČ„āíťĖč„ĀĎ„Ā¶‚Ė†ÁŅľ‚Ė†Soul%36s Food (La Luz) - Radio Version‚Ė†Dream‚Ė†Catch You Catch Me‚Ė†Open the Door‚Ė†Dreaming‚Ė†Rashiku Ikimasho (off vocal ver.)‚Ė†Ai wo Shizumeteru‚Ė†Tobira wo akete (instrumental)‚Ė†Kanata e‚Ė†Tsubasa ~instrumental~‚Ė†Condesa‚Ė†Kanata he ~instrumental~‚Ė†Tsubasa (Kan