(224, 'Come Together (A Tribute To Bravo)', NULL, '120', '2006.06.10.', 'Polydor', 'Pop Rock;Rock;Punk', 'Come Together (A Tribute to BRAVO) is a tribute compilation album released in 2006 to commemorate the 50th anniversary of BRAVO, the most influential German-language teen magazine. The album serves as a cross-generational celebration of the publication\'s impact on European youth culture since its founding in 1956.\nThe compilation features a collection of cover versions of chart classic songs that defined the music industry and dominated the BRAVO charts over the previous five decades. In a thematic nod to the magazine\'s focus on teen idols, the tracks are performed by contemporary teenage stars and popular artists who were frequently featured in the magazine\'s coverage at the time of the album\'s release.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, 'b4579413-535b-4f12-a8a4-693e849338fd', '~Caravan of Love~[{Mike Engles_not_found};{Ernie Isley_not_found};{Marvin Isley_not_found};{Chris Jasper_not_found}]‚Ė†‚Ė†‚Ė†~Blaue Augen~[{Annette Humpe_not_found}]‚Ė†~Skandal im Sperrbezirk~[{G√ľnther Sigl_not_found}]‚Ė†~Wouldn‚Äôt It Be Good~[{Nik Kershaw_not_found}]‚Ė†~Like a Virgin~[{Tom Kelly_not_found};{Billy Steinberg_not_found}]‚Ė†~Club Tropicana~[{George Michael_not_found};{Andrew Ridgeley_not_found}]‚Ė†~Do Ya Think I‚ĖÄm Sexy~[{Carmine Appice_not_found};{Duane Hitchings_not_found};{Rod Stewart_not_found}]‚Ė†~End of the Road~[{Babyface_not_found};{L.A. Reid_not_found};{Daryl Simmons_not_found}]‚Ė†~Du liebst mich nicht~[{Martin Haas_not_found};{Moses Pelham_not_found}]‚Ė†‚Ė†~Kinder an die Macht~[{Nick Davis_not_found};{Herbert Gr√∂nemeyer_not_found}]‚Ė†~Horizont~[{Udo Lindenberg_not_found}]‚Ė†~Instant Karma~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~S.O.S.~[{Various Artists_not_found}]', '~Caravan of Love~{Duncan Townsend_not_found};{The Housemartins_not_found}]', '~Caravan of Love~[{by Nena_not_found}]‚Ė†~Instant Karma~[{John Lennon_not_found}]‚Ė†~S.O.S.~[{ABBA_not_found}]‚Ė†~Blaue Augen~[{Ideal_not_found}]‚Ė†~Skandal im Sperrbezirk~[{Spider Murphy Gang_not_found}]‚Ė†~Wouldn‚Äôt It Be Good~[{Nik Kershaw_not_found}]‚Ė†~Like a Virgin~[{Madonna_not_found}]‚Ė†~Club Tropicana~[{Wham!_not_found}]‚Ė†~Do Ya Think I‚Ėąm Sexy~[{Rod Stewart_not_found}]‚Ė†~End of the Road~[{Boyz II Men_not_found}]‚Ė†~Du liebst mich nicht~[{Sabrina Setlur_not_found}]‚Ė†~Da Da Da~[{Trio_not_found}]‚Ė†~Kinder an die Macht~[{Herbert Gr√∂nemeyer_not_found}]‚Ė†~Horizont~[{Udo Lindenberg_not_found}]'),
(225, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Kodansha CD Comic', NULL, '120', '1997.08.07.', 'Kodansha', 'Anime', 'Kodansha CD Comic: Cardcaptor Sakura (Ť¨õŤęáÁ§ĺCD„ā≥„Éü„ÉÉ„āĮ „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ) is a multimedia \"CD comic\" released on August 7, 1997. Published by Kodansha, it served as a major promotional tie-in for the Cardcaptor Sakura manga series by the artist group CLAMP. Released nearly eight months before the premiere of the 1998 anime adaptation, the disc is notable for featuring the debut of the voice cast that would define the franchise for decades.\nThe \"CD Comic\" was a specific marketing format used in Japan during the 1990s to generate interest in manga properties. It typically bundled a physical booklet (containing short manga stories or illustrations) with a Compact Disc.\nUnlike standard drama CDs, which usually adapt existing manga chapters faithfully, this release acted as an audio-visual hybrid. It introduced the \"official\" voices of the characters to the public for the first time, establishing the performances of Sakura Tange (Sakura Kinomoto), Junko Iwao (Tomoyo Daidouji), and Aya Hisakawa (Kero-chan).', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '', '~Cardcaptor Sakura~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Asa Sakura no Uchi~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Asa Sakura no Class~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Eyecatch~Sakura no Uchi~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Yoru Tomoeda Shougakkou~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Shiawase no Mahou~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†~Yoru no Uta~[{Various Artists_not_found}]', NULL, NULL),
(226, 'Cardcaptor Sakura ORIGINAL DRAMA ALBUM 1 - Sakura to Okaasan no Organ', NULL, '120', '1998.07.23.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Drama Album 1: Sakura to Okaasan no Organ („āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„ÉČ„É©„Éě„ÉĽ„āĘ„Éę„Éź„É†1 „Äú„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ„Ā®„ĀäśĮć„Āē„āď„Āģ„ā™„Éę„ā¨„É≥„Äú, lit. \"Sakura and Mother\'s Organ\") is the first official audio drama album based on the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise. Released on July 23, 1998, by Victor Entertainment, the album was produced during the initial broadcast of the first season of the anime series.\nWhile the previously released CD Comic served as a pilot for the voice cast, this album is a fully realized production set within the continuity of the Madhouse anime adaptation. It features a combination of scripted audio drama, character songs, and background music (BGM) composed by Takayuki Negishi.\nThe narrative is framed around the memories of Sakura‚Äôs deceased mother, Nadeshiko Kinomoto, and a specific musical instrument‚ÄĒan organ‚ÄĒthat serves as a sentimental link between the past and present.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '8ba2bade-0308-463d-97e1-827ad2fd299a', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(227, 'Cardcaptor Sakura ORIGINAL DRAMA ALBUM 2 - Sweet Valentine Stories', NULL, '120', '1999.02.10.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Drama Album 2: Sweet Valentine Stories („āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„ÉČ„É©„Éě„ÉĽ„āĘ„Éę„Éź„É†2 „Äú„āĻ„ā£„Éľ„Éą„ÉĽ„Éź„É¨„É≥„āŅ„ā§„É≥„ÉĽ„āĻ„Éą„Éľ„É™„Éľ„āļ„Äú) is the second official audio drama album based on the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise. Released on February 10, 1999, by Victor Entertainment, the album was timed to coincide with Valentine\'s Day and the peak popularity of the anime\'s second season (the \"Clow Card\" arc).\nFollowing the emotional, retrospective tone of the first drama album, Sweet Valentine Stories focuses on the ensemble cast\'s interpersonal relationships and the theme of \"giving\" (the tradition of Giri-choco and Honmei-choco). The album is noted for its lighter, more comedic tone compared to its predecessor, though it retains the series\' signature sentimental moments.\nThe narrative follows Sakura Kinomoto, Tomoyo Daidouji, and their classmates as they prepare for Valentine\'s Day. A central plot point involves the characters deciding who they want to give chocolates to, leading to various comedic misunderstandings and heartwarming interactions between the core cast.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '387a1caa-04db-4a67-8b29-39395d869f01', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(228, 'Cardcaptor Sakura - Tomoeda Shougakkou Chorus Christmas Concert', NULL, '120', '1999.12.01.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime;Christmas', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: Tomoeda Shougakkou Chorus-bu Christmas Concert („āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ ŚŹčśěĚŚįŹŚ≠¶ś†°„ā≥„Éľ„É©„āĻťÉ® „āĮ„É™„āĻ„Éě„āĻ„ÉĽ„ā≥„É≥„āĶ„Éľ„Éą, lit. \"Tomoeda Elementary School Chorus Club Christmas Concert\") is a Christmas-themed mini-album based on the Cardcaptor Sakura anime series. Released on December 1, 1999, by Victor Entertainment, the album is presented as a \"live recording\" of a holiday concert performed by the fictional choir of Sakura Kinomoto\'s school.\nThe album is unique within the franchise\'s discography for its focus on choral arrangements rather than standard J-pop or character songs. It serves as a diegetic expansion of the series, featuring Tomoyo Daidouji (voiced by Junko Iwao) as the lead soloist of the Tomoeda Elementary School Chorus Club.\nWhile the voices of the \"students\" are provided by the Suzukake Children\'s Choir, the arrangements were handled by the series\' main composer, Takayuki Negishi, and Shiro Hamaguchi.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '', '~Yoru no Uta~[{Various Artists_not_found}]‚Ė†‚Ė†‚Ė†‚Ė†‚Ė†‚Ė†', NULL, NULL),
(229, 'Cardcaptor Sakura - Sakura no Oshaberi Talk CD', NULL, '120', '1999.12.18.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: Sakura no Oshaberi Talk CD („āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „Āē„ĀŹ„āČ„Āģ„Āä„Āó„āÉ„ĀĻ„āä„Éą„Éľ„āĮCD, lit. \"Sakura\'s Chatty Talk CD\") is a special promotional mini-album released on December 18, 1999, by Victor Entertainment. Unlike the narrative-driven Original Drama Albums, this release focuses on \"out-of-character\" and meta-commentary segments featuring the series\' lead voice actress, Sakura Tange.\nThe \"Talk CD\" format was a popular niche in late-90s anime merchandising, serving as a bridge between the fictional world of the show and the real-life voice actors (seiyuu). This specific disc was marketed as a \"fan appreciation\" release during the winter of 1999, coinciding with the height of the \"Sakura Card\" arc on television.\nThe album is characterized by its informal, intimate tone, designed to give listeners the impression of sitting down for a private chat with the character Sakura Kinomoto and her voice actress.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(230, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Character Singles', NULL, '120', '1998.06.03.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'The Cardcaptor Sakura Character Singles are a series of character song CDs released by Victor Entertainment based on the anime adaptation of the CLAMP manga series. The collection consists of six individual 8cm mini-CD singles, each focusing on a primary character from the series.\nThe singles were released in two waves during the summer of 1998. Each disc features a vocal track performed by the character\'s voice actor (seiyŇę), an \"audio drama\" segment involving the protagonist Sakura Kinomoto, and an instrumental version of the main track. Volume 1 (Released June 3, 1998): Featured Sakura, Touya, and Kero and Volume 2 (Released June 24, 1998): Featured Syaoran, Tomoyo, and Yukito.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(231, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Character Songbook', NULL, '120', '1999.01.21.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Character Songbook (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā≠„É£„É©„āĮ„āŅ„Éľ„āĹ„É≥„āį„ÉĖ„ÉÉ„āĮ, Hepburn: KńĀdokyaputńĀ Sakura KyarakutńĀ Songubukku) is a character album featuring vocal tracks from the anime series Cardcaptor Sakura. Released on January 21, 1999, by Victor Entertainment, it serves as the first major vocal compilation for the franchise.\nThe album differs from the previously released individual singles by featuring new arrangements, duet tracks, and a cohesive \"school-day\" theme reflected in the booklet artwork.\nThe album contains ten tracks, including solo songs for the main cast and a group performance of the first opening theme, \"Catch You Catch Me.\" Notable additions to this release include the first character song for Meiling Li and a duet between Sakura and Tomoyo.\nThe music was primarily composed and arranged by Takayuki Negishi, who also handled the series\' background music (BGM), ensuring a consistent sonic palette with the TV show.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '8ba2bade-0308-463d-97e1-827ad2fd299a', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(232, 'Cardcaptor Sakura COMPLETE VOCAL COLLECTION', NULL, '120', '2001.02.21.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: Complete Vocal Collection (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā≥„É≥„Éó„É™„Éľ„Éą„ÉĽ„Éú„Éľ„āę„Éę„ÉĽ„ā≥„É¨„āĮ„ā∑„Éß„É≥, Hepburn: KńĀdokyaputńĀ Sakura Konpurńęto BŇćkaru Korekushon) is a four-disc box set featuring the definitive collection of vocal music from the anime television series and its two feature films. Released on February 21, 2001, by Victor Entertainment, it serves as a comprehensive retrospective of the franchise\'s musical output.\nThe collection includes all opening and ending themes, character songs previously released on singles and songbooks, and vocal tracks from the movies. The box set was released following the conclusion of the original television run and the second film, The Sealed Card. It is notable for its premium packaging, which originally included a 60-page booklet featuring lyrics, staff interviews, and exclusive illustrations by CLAMP.', NULL, NULL, '3', NULL, '05bcce25-f91b-4577-bcb1-f7a9c973f091', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(233, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack', NULL, '141', '1998.07.23.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ) is the first soundtrack album for the anime television series Cardcaptor Sakura. Released on July 23, 1998, by Victor Entertainment, it features the background music (BGM) used during the first season of the show, as well as several vocal theme songs.\nThe music was primarily composed and arranged by Takayuki Negishi, who drew from classical and orchestral influences to match the magical and whimsical tone of the series.\nThe soundtrack serves as the musical introduction to the series, covering the \"Clow Card\" arc. It is the first of four television soundtracks released for the original run. The cover art features an illustration by CLAMP, depicting the protagonist Sakura Kinomoto in her first battle costume.\nThe album is notable for including the full version of the iconic first opening theme, \"Catch You Catch Me,\" performed by GUMI (Megumi Hinata), and the insert song \"Yoru no Uta\" (Song of the Night), which became a signature track for the character Tomoyo Daidouji.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '257861d4-57e1-48a3-8896-ecd084d2de34', '~Sakura no THEME II~[{Takayuki Negishi_not_found}]‚Ė†~Yume~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tanoshii Hitotoki~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sawayakana Asa~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yo Te Atrapo‚Ė† Tu Me Atrapas~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yo Te Atrapo‚Ė† Tu Me Atrapas~[{481}]', NULL, NULL),
(234, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 2', NULL, '141', '1998.12.19.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 2 (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ2) is the second soundtrack album for the anime television series Cardcaptor Sakura. Released on December 19, 1998, by Victor Entertainment, it continues the musical documentation of the series\' first season, focusing on the introduction of new characters and the escalating stakes of the \"Clow Card\" arc.\nThe album features background music (BGM) composed by Takayuki Negishi, along with new vocal tracks and various \"TV-size\" versions of the series\' themes.\nThe soundtrack is notable for the inclusion of themes for characters introduced later in the first season, specifically Meiling Li and the mysterious teacher Kaho Mizuki. The cover art features Sakura Kinomoto alongside Yukito Tsukishiro, reflecting the romantic subplots prominent in this portion of the series.\nKey highlights include the \"Sakura Version\" of the first opening theme, performed by Sakura Tange herself, and the full version of the first ending theme, \"Groovy!\", by Kohmi Hirose.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', 'de5aa6bb-56e0-4da5-8424-8bd809ca9631', '~Fuuin-kaijo~[{481}]‚Ė†~Catch You Catch Me~[{481}]‚Ė†~Roller Blade~[{481}]‚Ė†~Meilin no Teema (Meilin‚ĖÄs Theme)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Card no Kehai (Sensing a Card)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yume ni Mita Date (Date Which I‚ĖÄve Dreamed Of)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tsuiseki (Chase)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kaho no Teema (Kaho‚ĖÄs Theme)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Shopping~[{481}]‚Ė†~Dokidoki Danken-tai (An Excited Expedition)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Chiisana Yousei (A Small Fairy)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Musekinin‚ĖÄna Shugosha (The Irresponsible Guardian)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Dota-bata (Slapstick)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Deai (Encounter)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Super Duper Love Love Days~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yochou (Omen)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Card no Kougeki (Attack of a Card)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yasashisa ni Tsutsumarete (Wrapped in Tenderness)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hoshi no Kirameki (Twinkle of Stars)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Nukumori no Kioku (Memories of Warmth)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kai-genshou (Mysterious Phenomenon)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kanashii Na (I Feel Sad)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Maboroshi (Illusion)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Dai-pinchi (Real Crisis)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ketsui (Determination)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sakura Gambaru (Sakura Shows Her Guts)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Victory~[{481}]‚Ė†~Subtitle~[{481}]‚Ė†~Eye Catch~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yokoku BGM (BGM for Preview)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kero-chan ni Omakase (Leave It to Kero-chan)~[{481}]‚Ė†~Groovy!~[{481}]', '~Catch You Catch Me~{Sakura Tange]_not_found}]‚Ė†~Super Duper Love Love Days~{Megumi Hinata]_not_found}]', NULL),
(235, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 3', NULL, '141', '1999.06.23.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 3 (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ3) is the third soundtrack album for the anime television series Cardcaptor Sakura. Released on June 23, 1999, by Victor Entertainment, the album marks the musical transition from the \"Clow Card\" arc to the \"Sakura Card\" arc (the series\' second and third seasons).\nThe score, composed and arranged by Takayuki Negishi, shifts toward a more sophisticated and slightly darker tone to reflect the arrival of Eriol Hiiragizawa and the transformation of the cards.\nThe soundtrack is notable for introducing the second opening theme, \"Tobira wo Akete\" (Open the Door), and the second ending theme, \"Honey.\" The cover art features Sakura Kinomoto in her iconic pink \"star\" costume, which debuted alongside her new Star Power wand.\nA significant portion of the album is dedicated to the mysterious atmosphere surrounding the new antagonist, Eriol, featuring heavier use of pipe organs, bells, and synthesized choral textures compared to the previous two soundtracks.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '1f30fa27-6f9a-46d0-bcb7-95c2441f6946', '~Clow Reed No Densetsu~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hangeki Kaishi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Shinobi Yoru Kage~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kyouteki Shutsugen~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kusen~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yoru No Uta~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ganbare Sakura~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mou Hitori No Shugosha~[{481}]‚Ė†~Fuuin No Kemono Cerberus~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tomo He~[{481}]‚Ė†~Saigo No Card~[{481}]‚Ė†~Saigo No Shinpan~[{481}]‚Ė†~Omoide Ga Kiechau~[{481}]‚Ė†~Shinpan Zokkou~[{481}]‚Ė†~Card Wo Tugumono~[{481}]‚Ė†~Suki To Iu Kimochi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tobira wo Akete~[{481}]‚Ė†~Honey~[{481}]', NULL, NULL),
(236, 'Cardcaptor Sakura - The Movie Original Soundtrack', NULL, '141', '1999.08.25.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: The Movie Original Soundtrack (Japanese: ŚäáŚ†īÁČą„āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ) is the soundtrack album for the first animated feature film in the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise. Released on August 25, 1999, by Victor Entertainment, the album features the orchestral score composed by Takayuki Negishi and the film\'s vocal theme.\nSet in Hong Kong, the film‚Äôs music represents a departure from the \"school life\" atmosphere of the TV series, incorporating traditional Chinese musical elements to reflect the new setting.\nUnlike the television soundtracks, which featured many short, episodic cues, the movie soundtrack consists of longer, more cinematic arrangements. Takayuki Negishi utilized a full orchestra and integrated traditional instruments, such as the erhu and pipa, to create the \"Hong Kong\" atmosphere.\nThe score emphasizes the mystery of the \"Madoushi\" (The Su-Yung Spirit) and the history of Clow Reed. The album also includes the film\'s ending theme, \"Tooi Kono Machi de\", which became one of the most recognizable ballads in the series.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '', '~Prelude~[{481}]‚Ė†~Spring Night Love Song~[{481}]‚Ė†~Temptation Of Water~[{481}]‚Ė†~Worry Over The School Report~[{481}]‚Ė†~The Fun Is Yet To Come~[{481}]‚Ė†~Suddenly To Hong Kong~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sakura‚Ė† The Gourmet~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tension Looming Up~[{481}]‚Ė†~To A Foreign Country~[{481}]‚Ė†~Beautiful Visage~[{481}]‚Ė†~Woman In Dream~[{481}]‚Ė†~Give Me Power~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hidden Secret~[{481}]‚Ė†~Trap Of The Small Birds~[{481}]‚Ė†~Absolutely Astonished~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mysterious World Of Water~[{481}]‚Ė†~A Fuse Of Battle~[{481}]‚Ė†~Gathering Courage~[{481}]‚Ė†~Storm Of Fury~[{481}]‚Ė†~Memories Of Clow~[{481}]‚Ė†~Who‚ĖÄs There!~[{481}]‚Ė†~Beyond The Forbidden Area~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mysterious Chaser~[{481}]‚Ė†~Start Of Counterattack~[{481}]‚Ė†~The Final Counterattack~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sakura In Imminent Danger~[{481}]‚Ė†~The Sorceress‚ĖÄs Love~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hair Ornament Wet With Tears~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tooi Kono Machi De~[{481}]', NULL, NULL),
(237, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 4', NULL, '141', '2000.03.23.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Original Soundtrack 4 (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ4) is the fourth and final soundtrack album for the original anime television series. Released on March 23, 2000, by Victor Entertainment, it contains the musical score for the final stretch of the \"Sakura Card\" arc, leading up to the series finale.\nThe album features the most iconic opening of the franchise, \"Platinum,\" performed by Maaya Sakamoto, and the final ending theme, \"Fruits Candy.\"\nComposer Takayuki Negishi reaches a thematic peak in this volume, blending the whimsical elements of earlier seasons with a grand, orchestral scale. This soundtrack introduces the themes for the final trials orchestrated by Eriol Hiiragizawa, as well as the music for the \"Last Judgement\" and the ultimate transformation of the Clow Cards into Sakura Cards.\nThe score is notably more dramatic than previous volumes, utilizing heavy brass, rapid string sections, and choral arrangements to underscore the high stakes of the final episodes.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', 'e8c40fb0-ff5b-4a06-9193-5599cb1a4448', '~Clow Reed no Theme~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hoshi no Chikara~[{481}]‚Ė†~Eriol no Theme~[{481}]‚Ė†~Nakuru no Theme~[{481}]‚Ė†~Clow Reed no Kage~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mou Hitori no Eriol~[{481}]‚Ė†~Shoushin na Shin‚ĖÄnyuusha~[{481}]‚Ė†~Koi-gokoro~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ashidori Karuku~[{481}]‚Ė†~MOJI-MOJI~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hoshi no Michi no Kokuhaku~[{481}]‚Ė†~Heartbreak~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sorezore no Omoi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Suki tte nandarou~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kureyuku Hitotose~[{481}]‚Ė†~Shoutai~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tooi hi no Wakare~[{481}]‚Ė†~Eien no Yami~[{481}]‚Ė†~Saigo no Shiren~[{481}]‚Ė†~Zettai Daijoubu~[{481}]‚Ė†~Atarashii Aruji~[{481}]‚Ė†~Honto no Ichiban~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hitotsu Dake~[{481}]‚Ė†~Platinum~[{481}]‚Ė†~FRUITS CANDY~[{481}]', '~Kureyuku Hitotose~{Cardcaptor Sakura Cast]_not_found}]', NULL),
(238, 'Cardcaptor Sakura Movie 2 - The Sealed Card Original Soundtrack', NULL, '141', '2000.08.02.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura Movie 2: The Sealed Card Original Soundtrack (Japanese: ŚäáŚ†īÁČą„āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ ŚįĀŚćį„Āē„āĆ„Āü„āę„Éľ„ÉČ „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ) is the soundtrack album for the second and final animated feature film of the original series. Released on August 2, 2000, by Victor Entertainment, it serves as the musical finale to the 1990s Cardcaptor Sakura era. The score was composed and arranged by Takayuki Negishi. It is widely regarded as his most sophisticated work for the franchise, featuring a heavy emphasis on a full orchestral sound to match the film\'s cinematic scale and emotional weight.\nAs the film serves as the definitive conclusion to the story and the resolution of the romance between Sakura Kinomoto and Syaoran Li, the soundtrack is characterized by grand, sweeping romantic themes alongside darker, suspenseful cues for the \"Nothing\" card. The album is notable for the inclusion of the film\'s theme song, \"Ashita e no Melody\" (Melody to Tomorrow), a powerful ballad performed by CHAKA. It also includes the insert song \"Arigatou\" (Thank You), a sentimental track performed by Sakura\'s voice actress, Sakura Tange.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '', '~A`itakatta~[{481}]', NULL, NULL),
(239, 'Cardcaptor Sakura - Clear Card Original Soundtrack', NULL, '141', '2018.06.13.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card Original Soundtrack (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „āĮ„É™„āĘ„āę„Éľ„ÉČÁ∑® „ā™„É™„āł„Éä„Éę„ÉĽ„āĶ„ā¶„É≥„ÉČ„Éą„É©„ÉÉ„āĮ) is the soundtrack album for the 2018 anime television series Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card. Released on June 13, 2018, by FlyingDog (a subsidiary of Victor Entertainment), it marks the return of the franchise after an 18-year hiatus. The music was composed and arranged by Takayuki Negishi, who returned to the series to provide a modernized yet nostalgic score that bridged the gap between the original 1990s production and the new era of the franchise.\nUnlike the more MIDI-heavy and synth-pop arrangements of the late 90s, the Clear Card soundtrack features higher production values and a more prominent use of live orchestral recordings. Negishi intentionally revisited several iconic motifs from the original series‚ÄĒsuch as Sakura\'s and Syaoran\'s character themes‚ÄĒand re-arranged them with updated instrumentation. The score introduces new \"mystical\" textures to represent the translucent nature of the Clear Cards, utilizing glockenspiels, harps, and ethereal woodwinds. It also includes the TV-size versions of the series\' themes, most notably \"CLEAR\" by Maaya Sakamoto, which serves as a spiritual successor to her 1999 hit \"Platinum.\"', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '', '~Tomei na Mirai~[{481}]‚Ė†~CLEAR~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kyo kara Chugakusei~[{481}]‚Ė†~Clear Card Shutsugen~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sakura no Shinseikatsu~[{481}]‚Ė†~UkiUki Odekake~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tomadoi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Nazo no Chikara~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yosoku Dekinai~[{481}]‚Ė†~Watashi wo Ugokasu Chikara~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yureru Kimochi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Sora wa Miteiruyo~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yuyake ni chikatta~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ieji~[{481}]‚Ė†~On the Special Day~[{481}]‚Ė†~Nakayoshi Friends~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mada Toku ni Iru~[{481}]‚Ė†~Oborozukiyo~[{481}]‚Ė†~Majutsushi~[{481}]‚Ė†~Abareru Card~[{481}]‚Ė†~Zettai Makenai~[{481}]‚Ė†~Secure!~[{481}]‚Ė†~Moso Daibakuhatsu!~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ashita ga Iihide Aruyoni~[{481}]‚Ė†~ROCKET BEAT~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yasuragi no Ie~[{481}]‚Ė†~DOGI-MAGI~[{481}]‚Ė†~Koko ni Kite~[{481}]‚Ė†~Kung-fu Action!~[{481}]‚Ė†~Isekaieno Tobira~[{481}]‚Ė†~Ore ga Mamoru~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tsukanomano Heiwa~[{481}]‚Ė†~Rewind~[{481}]‚Ė†~Koishiteru~[{481}]‚Ė†~Jikan wo Ayatsuru Otoko~[{481}]‚Ė†~Hatsudosareta Maryoku~[{481}]‚Ė†~Soradatte Toberu~[{481}]‚Ė†~Mamorubekimono~[{481}]‚Ė†~Yakusoku no Sora~[{481}]‚Ė†~Jewelry~[{481}]', '~Sora wa Miteiruyo~{Junko Iwao]_not_found}]‚Ė†~Yakusoku no Sora~{Junko Iwao]_not_found}]', NULL),
(240, 'Cardcaptor Sakura  - The Best Collection', NULL, '141', '2000.08.02.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Cardcaptor Sakura: The Best Collection (Japanese: „āę„Éľ„ÉČ„ā≠„É£„Éó„āŅ„Éľ„Āē„ĀŹ„āČ „Éô„āĻ„Éą„ÉĽ„ā≥„É¨„āĮ„ā∑„Éß„É≥, Hepburn: KńĀdokyaputńĀ Sakura Besuto Korekushon) is a compilation album featuring the primary theme songs from the anime television series and its first feature film. Released on August 2, 2000, by Victor Entertainment, it was launched on the same day as the The Sealed Card movie soundtrack to celebrate the peak of the franchise\'s popularity.Unlike the later Complete Vocal Collection, which served as an exhaustive 4-disc archive, The Best Collection was designed as a \"greatest hits\" single-disc release for casual listeners.\n\nThe album compiles the three opening themes and three ending themes from the TV series, as well as the theme song from the first movie. It is particularly notable for including the \"solo\" versions of the first opening and ending, and for featuring the high-fidelity versions of tracks that were previously only available on individual 8cm mini-CD singles. The cover art features an iconic illustration of Sakura Kinomoto in her \"Star\" costume, holding her wand against a backdrop of the Clow Cards, symbolizing the completion of her journey.', 'Synthesizer', NULL, '141_bnd', '481', '', '~Sakura Drama Album 2 ‚ĖÄSweet Valentine Stories‚ĖÄ~[{481}]‚Ė†~FRUITS CANDY~[{481}]‚Ė†~Platinum~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tooi Kono Machi De~[{481}]‚Ė†~Honey~[{481}]‚Ė†~Tobira wo Akete~[{481}]‚Ė†~Groovy!~[{481}]‚Ė†~Catch You Catch Me~[{481}]‚Ė†~Picnic~[{481}]‚Ė†~6th Story Tomoyo~[{481}]‚Ė†~Get Your Love~[{481}]‚Ė†~5th Story Meiling~[{481}]', NULL, NULL),
(241, 'Tooi Kono Machi De', NULL, '142', '1998.08.11.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Anime', '\"Tooi Kono Machi de\" (Japanese: ťĀ†„ĀĄ„Āď„ĀģŤ°ó„Āß, lit. \"In This Distant Town\") is a J-pop song by Japanese singer-songwriter Naomi Kaitani. It was released as her debut single on August 11, 1999, through Victor Entertainment. The song served as the ending theme for the 1999 animated film Cardcaptor Sakura: The Movie. The track is widely considered one of the most emotional ballads in the Cardcaptor Sakura discography, specifically written to capture the film\'s themes of travel, longing, and the transition from childhood.\n\"Tooi Kono Machi de\" was composed and written by Naomi Kaitani specifically for the Cardcaptor Sakura film. The arrangement was handled by Akihiko Fumi, who utilized a blend of acoustic piano, sweeping string sections, and a subtle pop percussion track to create a \"cinematic\" ballad feel.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '142_bnd', '482', '8fcb9386-ffe8-46b8-b7c8-17ed0b9cf68b', '~Tooi Kono Machi De~[{Naomi Kaitani_not_found}]‚Ė†~Sepia no Hi~[{Naomi Kaitani_not_found}]', NULL, NULL),
(242, 'Miru Mae ni Tobe!', NULL, '153', '2018.12.19.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Anime', 'Miru Mae ni Tobe! (Japanese: Ť¶č„āčŚČć„Āęť£õ„ĀĻÔľĀ, lit. \"Jump Before You Look!\") is the debut studio album by Japanese singer and voice actress Minori Suzuki. Released on December 19, 2018, by FlyingDog, the album marked a major milestone in her solo career following her breakout role as Freyja Wion in the anime series Macross Delta. The album features a blend of J-pop and anisong styles, incorporating 12 tracks including several of her early hit singles used as theme songs for various anime series.\nFollowing her debut as part of the idol group Walk√ľre, Suzuki began her solo music career in early 2018. Miru Mae ni Tobe! was conceived as a comprehensive introduction to her musical identity, showcasing her versatile vocal range. The album title‚ÄĒa play on the common proverb \"look before you leap\"‚ÄĒreflects an adventurous and \"jump-first\" attitude toward her new career path. The album was released in two formats: a Regular Edition (CD) and a Limited Edition, which bundled a Blu-ray featuring music videos and documentary footage.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '153_bnd', '483', '', '~Miru Mae ni Tobe!~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Hen na Koto ga Shitai!~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Suki na Mono wa Suki!~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Osenchi na Mental~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Crosswalk~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Ichiban Saigo no Natsu~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Hanonkai no Resistance~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~FEELING AROUND~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Watashi wa Watashi ni Naritai~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~astro traveler~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Rewind~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Kokoro ga‚Ė† Aoi.~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~20-Sai no Yakusoku~[{483}]‚Ė†~Chiisana Minori~[{483}]‚Ė†~Daisuki ni Natte Yokatta~[{483}]', NULL, NULL),
(243, 'FEELING AROUND', NULL, '153', '2018.01.24.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Anime', '\"Feeling Around\" is the debut solo single by Japanese singer and voice actress Minori Suzuki. Released on January 24, 2018, by FlyingDog, the song served as the opening theme for the anime television series Ms. Koizumi Loves Ramen Noodles (Ramen Daisuki Koizumi-san). The single marked Suzuki\'s transition into a solo career after her high-profile debut as the voice of Freyja Wion in Macross Delta and her participation in the idol group Walk√ľre.\nThe title track was written and composed by Koji Mihara of the rock band Frederic. It features the band\'s signature \"looping\" melodic style and wordplay, blended with a brass-heavy J-pop arrangement. The track was sound-produced by Yusuke Tanaka (known for his work with Ikimonogakari), designed to capture both the quirky, comedic nature of the anime and Suzuki\'s energetic vocal persona.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '153_bnd', '483', 'c6f6ebd8-4ca4-4ade-8d37-48b51c22897d', '~FEELING AROUND~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Suki na Mono wa Suki!~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~20-Sai no Yakusoku~[{483}]', NULL, NULL),
(244, 'Crosswalk - Rewind', NULL, '153', '2018.05.09.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Anime', '\"Crosswalk - Rewind\" is the second solo single by Japanese singer and voice actress Minori Suzuki. Released on May 9, 2018, by FlyingDog, the release is a double A-side single featuring two major tie-ins for anime series airing at the time.The single followed the success of her debut, \"Feeling Around,\" and further established Suzuki as a prominent solo artist in the anisong industry.\nThe single is unique for its high-profile creative collaborations, featuring contributions from established industry veterans. \"Crosswalk\": Used as the opening theme for the anime Amanchu! Advance. The lyrics were written by acclaimed singer-songwriter Maaya Sakamoto, with composition and arrangement by Katsutoshi Kitagawa (of the band Round Table). The song is a gentle, sweeping ballad that reflects the coastal, atmospheric setting of the anime.\n\"Rewind\": Used as the second ending theme for Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card. It was written, composed, and arranged by Yusuke Shirato. In contrast to \"Crosswalk,\" \"Rewind\" is an upbeat, nostalgic pop track that fits the magical girl aesthetic of the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '153_bnd', '483', '', '~Chiisana Minori~[{483}]‚Ė†~Crosswalk~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Rewind~[{Minori Suzuki_not_found}]‚Ė†~Daisuki ni Natte Yokatta~[{483}]', NULL, NULL),
(245, 'FRUITS CANDY', NULL, '152', '1999.11.20.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime;J-Pop', '\"Fruits Candy\" is a J-pop song performed by Japanese singer and voice actress Megumi Kojima. Released on April 26, 2000, the track gained significant recognition as the third ending theme for the popular anime series Cardcaptor Sakura, appearing in episodes 47 through 69.\nThe song is characterized by its upbeat, \"sugar-pop\" production and brass-heavy instrumentation, capturing the whimsical and optimistic tone of the series\' \"Sakura Card\" arc. It was composed by Hiroshi Koizumi with lyrics written by YŇęho Iwasato, a prolific lyricist known for her work on various high-profile anime soundtracks.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '484', '484', 'ab5883b2-f4c3-44ba-83b1-874959e422a9', '~FRUITS CANDY~[{484}]', NULL, NULL),
(246, 'Catch You Catch Me', NULL, '151', '1999.04.22.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Anime;J-Pop;Pop Rock', '\"Catch You Catch Me\" is the debut single by Japanese singer-songwriter Megumi Hinata (performing under the moniker meg rock). Released on April 22, 1998, the track gained international recognition as the first opening theme song for the hit anime series Cardcaptor Sakura, produced by Madhouse. The song is characterized by its upbeat, bubblegum pop production and themes of youthful infatuation and courage. It was written and composed by Kohmi Hirose, a prolific J-pop artist known as the \"Queen of Winter,\" and arranged by Hirose in collaboration with Akimitsu Honma.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '485', '485', '3aebbf4e-4471-434a-8b7b-2728c3caeacc', '~Catch You Catch Me~[{485}]‚Ė†~Hitorijime~[{485}]', NULL, NULL),
(247, 'Single Collection+Hotchpotch', NULL, '150', '1999.12.16.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop;Pop Rock', 'Single Collection+ Hotchpotch (stylized as Single Collection+ [Hotchpotch]) is the first compilation album by Japanese singer and voice actress Maaya Sakamoto, released on December 16, 1999, through Victor Entertainment.The album serves as a definitive bridge between Sakamoto‚Äôs early career and her transition into the 2000s. Produced primarily by her long-time collaborator Yoko Kanno, the collection features a mixture of single A-sides, B-sides, and soundtrack contributions from 1996 to 1999.\nUnlike a standard \"Greatest Hits,\" Hotchpotch functions as a thematic archive of Sakamoto\'s work in the anime industry. It includes her debut single \"Yakusoku wa Iranai,\" famously used as the opening theme for The Vision of Escaflowne, alongside tracks from Cardcaptor Sakura, Record of Lodoss War, and Clamp School Detectives.\nThe title \"Hotchpotch\" (a synonym for hodgepodge) refers to the diverse range of genres explored on the record, spanning orchestral pop: Large-scale arrangements typical of Kanno‚Äôs work, acoustic ballads: Stripped-back tracks highlighting Sakamoto\'s clear, \"crystalline\" vocal tone and experimental electronica: Early forays into trip-hop and synth-pop.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '486', '486', '74729a4a-a08f-4768-90e1-26da33629570', '~Yakusoku wa Iranai~[{486}]‚Ė†~Tomodachi~[{486}]‚Ė†~Bokura no Rekishi~[{486}]‚Ė†~Gift~[{486}]‚Ė†~Kimi ni Ai ni Ikou~[{486}]‚Ė†~Hikari no Naka e~[{486}]‚Ė†~Light of love~[{486}]‚Ė†~Kiseki no Umi~[{486}]‚Ė†~Active Heart~[{486}]‚Ė†~Pilot~[{486}]‚Ė†~Platinum~[{486}]‚Ė†~24 (twenty-four)~[{486}]‚Ė†~Koibito ni Tsuite~[{486}]‚Ė†~Pocket wo Kara ni Shite~[{486}]‚Ė†~CALL YOUR NAME~[{486}]‚Ė†~24~[{486}]', NULL, NULL),
(248, 'Single Collection+Achikochi', NULL, '150', '2020.07.15.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Singer-Songwriter', 'Single Collection+ Achikochi („ā∑„É≥„āį„Éę„ā≥„É¨„āĮ„ā∑„Éß„É≥+ „āĘ„ÉĀ„ā≥„ÉĀ) is the fourth compilation album released by Japanese singer and voice actress Maaya Sakamoto. Published on July 15, 2020, to commemorate the 25th anniversary of her debut, the album serves as a sequel to her previous \"Single Collection\" series (Hotchpotch, Nikopachi, and Mitsubachi).\nThe album is a comprehensive double-disc release that gathers Sakamoto\'s work from 2013 to 2020. It includes hit singles, tie-ins for various anime series and games, and several \"rarities\" that had not been previously featured on her studio albums.\nThe title \"Achikochi\" (meaning \"here and there\" in Japanese) reflects the eclectic nature of the collection, pulling together tracks from diverse projects across nearly a decade of her career.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '486', '486', 'b3354492-5c90-45ac-be52-b60bea778dec', '~Be mine!~[{486}]‚Ė†~Replica~[{486}]‚Ė†~Gyakkou~[{486}]‚Ė†~Kuuhaku~[{486}]‚Ė†~Uchuu no Kioku~[{486}]‚Ė†~cloud 9~[{486}]‚Ė†~Flash~[{486}]‚Ė†~Anata wo Tamotsu Mono~[{486}]‚Ė†~Secrear~[{486}]‚Ė†~Arakawa Kokei (feat. Tomita Lab)~[{486}]‚Ė†~Lazy Line Painter Jane (feat. Atsushi Suemitsu)~[{486}]‚Ė†~Mada Ugoku (feat. Cornelius)~[{486}]‚Ė†~Tell me what the rain knows~[{486}]‚Ė†~Mikazuki~[{486}]‚Ė†~Sotsugyou Shashin~[{486}]‚Ė†~Kore Kara~[{486}]‚Ė†~Clover~[{486}]', NULL, NULL),
(249, 'Platinum', NULL, '150', '1999.10.21.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'Ballad;J-Pop;Anime', '\"Platinum\" (Japanese: „Éó„É©„ÉĀ„Éä, Hepburn: Purachina) is a song by Japanese singer and voice actress Maaya Sakamoto, released as her sixth single on October 21, 1999. Written by Yuho Iwasato and composed and produced by Yoko Kanno, the track served as the third and final opening theme for the anime series Cardcaptor Sakura during its \"Sakura Card\" arc (episodes 47‚Äď70).\nThe song is widely regarded as one of Sakamoto\'s signature tracks and a classic of the late-1990s anime era. It is characterized by its upbeat, orchestral J-pop arrangement and optimistic lyrics centered on the power of self-belief and dreams.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '486', '486', '80ff9e93-dbca-498d-927c-0aebaf8aa086', '~24 (Twenty-four)~[{486}]‚Ė†~Platinum~[{486}]‚Ė†~24~[{486}]', NULL, NULL),
(250, 'CLEAR', NULL, '150', '2018.01.31.', 'FlyingDog', 'J-Pop;Anime', '\"Clear\" is a song recorded by Japanese singer and voice actress Maaya Sakamoto. Released on January 31, 2018, it served as the first opening theme for the anime series Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card, marking Sakamoto‚Äôs return to the franchise nearly twenty years after her iconic 1999 hit \"Platinum.\" The track was written by Sakamoto herself, with composition and arrangement by Yoshiki Mizuno, a member of the popular J-pop trio Ikimonogakari. The song is an upbeat, guitar-driven J-pop track characterized by its \"transparent\" and airy sound, mirroring the themes of the Clear Card arc. Sakamoto‚Äôs lyrics focus on themes of personal growth, the passage of time, and the \"clear\" path toward the future, reflecting both the protagonist Sakura Kinomoto‚Äôs journey and Sakamoto\'s own evolution as an artist.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '486', '486', 'c5746d0e-a676-4027-856c-2839d7e5003f', NULL, NULL, NULL),
(251, 'The Best Love Winters', NULL, '149', '1998.11.11.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', 'The Best Love Winters is the first greatest hits compilation released by Japanese pop singer-songwriter and composer Kohmi Hirose, who\'s often dubbed the \"Queen of Winter\" due to her series of high-energy seasonal hits, was released on November 11, 1998, through Victor Entertainment. The album represents the commercial peak of Hirose\'s career. It debuted at #1 on the Oricon Weekly Albums Chart and maintained strong momentum throughout the winter season. It sold over 2.4 million copies, making it one of the best-selling albums in Japanese music history. It was certified Double Million by the Recording Industry Association of Japan (RIAJ). The compilation features a collection of her most successful singles, many of which were used in high-profile marketing campaigns for the Japanese sporting goods company Alpen. The tracklist highlights her signature style: soaring high notes, upbeat arrangements, and themes centered around winter romance and skiing culture.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '487', '487', '518b244b-14e8-45c8-9105-f6dfacc59460', '~Groovy!~[{487}]‚Ė†~„ÉĒ„āĘ„Éč„ā∑„ÉĘ~[{487}]‚Ė†~„É≠„Éě„É≥„āĻ„ĀģÁ•ěśßė~[{487}]', NULL, NULL),
(252, 'Groovy!', NULL, '149', '1998.09.23.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Groovy!\" is a song by Japanese singer-songwriter Kohmi Hirose, released on September 23, 1998. It is best known globally as the first ending theme for the iconic anime series Cardcaptor Sakura. The track marked a departure from the \"Winter Queen\" persona Hirose had cultivated through her massive ski-resort hits like \"Romance no Kamisama.\" \"Groovy!\" is characterized by its upbeat, funk-inspired pop arrangement, featuring a prominent bassline and brass sections that align with the title\'s energetic sentiment.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '487', '487', 'f98a6c9a-50c1-481e-a63f-908b05c773c4', '~Groovy!~[{487}]', NULL, NULL),
(253, 'Egao', NULL, '148', '2018.11.07.', 'FlyingDog', 'Anime;J-Pop', 'Egao. (stylized as ep:1 and subtitled Acoustic Mini Album) is the second mini-album by Japanese voice actress and singer Kiyono Yasuno. It was released on November 7, 2018, under the FlyingDog label. The album serves as a departure from the synth-pop and upbeat arrangements of her debut, Smile., opting instead for a \"pure\" acoustic sound. The mini-album features a collection of seven tracks, focusing on organic instrumentation such as piano, acoustic guitar, and strings to highlight Yasuno‚Äôs vocal clarity. The title, Egao. (meaning \"Smile\" or \"Smiling Face\"), acts as a thematic sequel to her first mini-album, though the full stop in the title signifies a more grounded and mature direction.\nEvery track on the album was recorded with live acoustic instruments, moving away from electronic production. The album features contributions from notable J-pop composers and musicians, including Katsutoshi Kitagawa (of Round Table), who served as a frequent collaborator and producer for Yasuno. The track \"Rocket Beat\" served as the second opening theme for the anime series Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card, rearranged here in an acoustic style specifically for this release.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '488', '488', '', '~Bokuno Venus~[{488}]‚Ė†~Fuwafuwato Shiteru~[{488}]‚Ė†~Egao~[{488}]‚Ė†~Wonder Shot~[{488}]‚Ė†~Kasukana Kanashimi~[{488}]‚Ė†~Nagekino Sora~[{488}]‚Ė†~ROCKET BEAT~[{488}]‚Ė†~Aitakute~[{488}]', NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `releases` (`relID`, `relTitle`, `relAltTitle`, `relFKbands`, `relDate`, `relFKcompanies`, `relFKsubgenres`, `relFKdesc`, `relFKinstruments`, `relDuration`, `relFKartists`, `relFKlineup`, `relReleaseCode`, `relFKwriters`, `relFKfeatures`, `relFKcovers`) VALUES
(254, 'ROCKET BEAT', NULL, '148', '2018.04.25.', 'FlyingDog', 'Anime;J-Pop', '\"Rocket Beat\" is a J-pop song recorded by Japanese singer and voice actress Kiyono Yasuno. Released on March 3, 2018, it served as the second opening theme song for the anime series Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card. The track is noted for its upbeat, brass-heavy arrangement and its lyrical themes of courage and moving toward the future. The song marked a significant milestone in Yasuno\'s solo career, being her first major tie-in with a high-profile anime franchise. It was written and composed by Katsutoshi Kitagawa (of the band Round Table), a frequent collaborator within the Cardcaptor Sakura musical universe.\n\nIt was released as a double A-side single alongside \"Logos,\" which served as the opening for Sousei no Aquarion Logos. An energetic blend of J-pop and Anisong, characterized by a driving rhythm section and melodic synth lines. \"Rocket Beat\" is set in a bright, major key with a fast tempo, designed to mirror the magical girl themes of the Clear Card series. The lyrics focus on the protagonist\'s growth, using metaphors of light, wind, and \"beating\" hearts to symbolize the momentum of adolescence.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '488', '488', '', '~Aitakute~[{488}]‚Ė†~ROCKET BEAT~[{488}]', NULL, NULL),
(255, 'JUNCTION', NULL, '147', '2018.12.19.', 'Warner Bros. Home Entertainment', 'J-Pop', 'JUNCTION is the second studio album by Japanese voice actress and singer Saori Hayami. It was released on December 19, 2018, under the Warner Bros. Home Entertainment label. The album follows her 2016 debut, Live Love Laugh, and serves as a thematic bridge reflecting her growth as a songwriter and artist. The album\'s title, JUNCTION, symbolizes a \"crossing point\" or \"connection,\" representing the intersection of Hayami‚Äôs career as a prolific voice actress and her identity as a solo musician. Unlike her previous work, which leaned heavily into bright, symphonic J-pop, JUNCTION explores a more sophisticated palette of jazz, city pop, and soft rock.\nA significant milestone for this album was Hayami\'s increased involvement in the creative process. She wrote the lyrics and composed the music for several tracks, including the lead song \"Let‚Äôs go out\" and the jazz-influenced \"Sunny Side Up.\" The album was praised by critics for its \"adult\" atmosphere and Hayami‚Äôs signature transparent, \"crystal-like\" vocal delivery.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '489', '489', 'b46f2c43-2f83-41bc-a39a-aaf0728ab8c9', '~Let Me Hear~[{489}]‚Ė†~Metro Night~[{489}]‚Ė†~Natsume to Sekiryou~[{489}]‚Ė†~Yume no Hate Made~[{489}]‚Ė†~Shiroi Heya~[{489}]‚Ė†~Shukufuku~[{489}]‚Ė†~Interlude - Forgiveness~[{489}]‚Ė†~SUNNY SIDE TERRACE~[{489}]‚Ė†~Bleu Noir~[{489}]‚Ė†~Little Forest~[{489}]‚Ė†~Jewelry~[{489}]‚Ė†~Bye Bye~[{489}]‚Ė†~Atarashii Ashita~[{489}]‚Ė†~Atataka na Yurushi~[{489}]', NULL, NULL),
(256, 'Jewelry', NULL, '147', '2018.03.28.', 'Warner Bros. Home Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Jewelry\" is a song by Japanese voice actress and singer Saori Hayami, released on March 28, 2018. Serving as her fourth solo single, the track is widely recognized as the first ending theme for the anime television series Cardcaptor Sakura: Clear Card. The single marked a significant milestone in Hayami\'s musical career as it was both written and composed by Hayami herself, showcasing her capabilities as a singer-songwriter. \"Jewelry\" is a mid-tempo J-pop track characterized by its bright, uplifting arrangement and Hayami‚Äôs signature crystalline vocal delivery. Lyrically, the song explores themes of sparkling moments, emotional growth, and the \"jewelry-like\" preciousness of everyday experiences, aligning with the magical girl aesthetic of the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise.\nThe song was well-received by fans and critics alike, peaking at number 14 on the Oricon Weekly Singles Chart. Its association with a high-profile legacy franchise like Cardcaptor Sakura helped solidify Hayami‚Äôs standing as a prominent solo artist within the voice acting industry. It was later included in her second full-length studio album, JUNCTION, released in December 2018.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '489', '489', '12136c5f-d094-413e-91f9-646afc397290', '~Kohakutou~[{489}]‚Ė†~Jewelry~[{489}]', NULL, NULL),
(257, 'Honey', NULL, '146', '1999.05.21.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Honey\" is a J-pop song recorded by Japanese singer-songwriter Chihiro (not to be confused with the artist Chihiro Onitsuka). Released on April 1, 1999, the track gained significant recognition as the second ending theme for the critically acclaimed anime series Cardcaptor Sakura, produced by Madhouse. The song debuted during the \"Sakura Card\" arc (Episode 36) and remained the closing theme through Episode 46. Characterized by its upbeat, \"shibuya-kei\" influenced pop sound and acoustic guitar riffs, \"Honey\" reflects the blossoming feelings and innocent romance central to the series\' middle act.\nThe single was released under the Victor Entertainment label. While Chihiro\'s discography is relatively niche compared to other Cardcaptor Sakura contributors like Maaya Sakamoto, \"Honey\" remains her most enduring work due to its association with the franchise‚Äôs peak popularity in the late 1990s. The accompanying animation for the ending theme features a stylistic departure from the show\'s standard art style, utilizing a soft-focus, pastel aesthetic. It primarily focuses on the protagonist, Sakura Kinomoto, engaging in domestic activities like baking and scrapbooking, emphasizing the \"slice-of-life\" warmth that balanced the show\'s magical girl action.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '490', '490', '', '~Honey~[{490}]', '~Honey~{Sakura Tange]_not_found}]', NULL),
(258, 'Ashita e no Melody', NULL, '145', '2000.07.12.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Ashita e no Melody\" (Japanese: śėéśó•„Āł„Āģ„É°„É≠„Éá„ā£; lit. \"Melody for Tomorrow\") is the second solo single by Japanese singer Chaka (formerly the lead vocalist of the jazz-pop duo Psychic TV). Released on July 12, 2000, under the Sony Music Entertainment Japan label, the song gained significant recognition as the ending theme for the theatrical anime film Cardcaptor Sakura Movie 2: The Sealed Card. The single marked a departure from Chaka‚Äôs more experimental and jazz-influenced roots, leaning into a sweeping, orchestral J-pop sound. It was produced and arranged by Hamaguchi Shiro, a renowned composer known for his work on the Final Fantasy series and One Piece.\nThe title track is a dramatic power ballad characterized by its lush string arrangements and Chaka‚Äôs wide vocal range. Lyrically, the song focuses on themes of courage, the passage of time, and the emotional resolution of the Cardcaptor Sakura series. The B-side, \"Toi Kono Machi de\" (In This Distant Town), also served as a theme for the Cardcaptor Sakura franchise, specifically for the first film released in 1999, making this single a definitive collection of Chaka‚Äôs contributions to the series.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '491', '491', '', '~Ashita e no Melody~[{491}]‚Ė†~Blue as the Sky~[{491}]', NULL, NULL),
(259, 'Okashi no Uta', NULL, '144', '2000.07.12.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Okashi no Uta\" (Japanese: „Āä„Āč„Āó„Āģ„ĀÜ„Āü, lit. \"The Candy Song\") is a character single by Japanese voice actress and singer Aya Hisakawa, released on July 12, 2000, under the Victor Entertainment label. The single features Hisakawa performing in-character as Cerberus (Kero-chan), the mascot protagonist from the popular anime and manga series Cardcaptor Sakura. The title track served as the ending theme for the short film Leave it to Kero-chan! („āĪ„É≠„Ā°„āÉ„āď„Āę„Āä„Āĺ„Āč„Āõ!), which was screened alongside the second feature-length film, Cardcaptor Sakura Movie 2: The Sealed Card. Unlike the more melodic and pop-oriented tracks typically associated with the series, \"Okashi no Uta\" is a high-energy, comedic song that highlights Kero-chan\'s well-known obsession with sweets and snacks. The lyrics consist of a rhythmic \"menu\" of various Japanese and Western confections, delivered with the character‚Äôs signature Osaka dialect.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '492', '492', '', '~Okashi no Uta~[{492}]', '~Okashi no Uta~{Yumi Touma]_not_found}]', NULL),
(260, 'Tobira wo Akete', NULL, '143', '1999.04.21.', 'Victor Entertainment', 'J-Pop', '\"Tobira wo Akete\" (Japanese: śČČ„āí„Āā„ĀĎ¬≠„Ā¶, lit. \"Open the Door\") is a J-pop single by Japanese singer Anza Oyama, released on April 21, 1999, under the Victor Entertainment label. The song is best known as the second opening theme for the critically acclaimed anime series Cardcaptor Sakura, appearing in episodes 36 through 46. Produced during a transitional period in Oyama\'s career‚ÄĒfollowing her multi-year stint as Sailor Moon in the Sera Myu musicals‚ÄĒthe single marked a significant step in her solo discography. The song is characterized by its upbeat, \"magical girl\" pop energy, featuring a blend of orchestral strings and electronic percussion typical of late-90s anime soundtracks.\nThe track was composed and arranged by Kohmi Hirose, a prolific singer-songwriter often dubbed the \"Queen of Winter\" in Japan. The lyrics, written by Kiyomi Kumano, focus on themes of courage, self-discovery, and the metaphorical \"opening of doors\" to the future, mirroring the protagonist Sakura Kinomoto‚Äôs growth during the \"Sakura Card\" arc of the series. The original CD single was released in the 8cm (mini-CD) format, which was the standard for Japanese singles at the time.', 'Lead Vocals', NULL, '493', '493', '54cff18c-b288-4d12-9068-d5087c4b5491', '~Tobira wo Akete~[{493}]‚Ė†~Mienai Chizu~[{493}]', NULL, NULL);
